{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=February 2020}}<!-- Please do not change without broad consensus. -->\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in New Zealand}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in New Zealand (DHB Totals).svg\n| legend1         = {{center|Map of the outbreak in New Zealand by district health board ({{as of|lc=y|2020|04|15}})}}\n{{legend|#510000|200+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#900000|100\u2013199 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#c80200|50\u201399 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ee7070|10\u201349 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[New Zealand]]\n| first_case      = [[Auckland]]\n| arrival_date    = 28 February 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|2020|02|28}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], China\n| confirmed_cases = 1,086<ref name=\"current cases\"/>\n| suspected_cases = 323<ref name=\"current cases\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 816<ref name=\"current cases\"/>\n| deaths          = 11<ref name=\"current cases\" />\n| total_ili       =\n| website         = {{URL|https://www.covid19.govt.nz}}\n}}\n\nThe first case of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[New Zealand]] was reported on 28 February 2020. {{as of|2020|4|17}}, the country has a total of 1,409 cases (1,086 confirmed and 323 probable{{efn|A probable case is where there is good cause to suspect that the patient has COVID-19, but testing is inconclusive or negative.}}) and eleven people have died from the virus.<ref name=\"current cases\">{{cite web|url=https://www.health.govt.nz/our-work/diseases-and-conditions/covid-19-novel-coronavirus/covid-19-current-cases|title=COVID-19 \u2013 current cases|date={{#time:Y-m-d}}|publisher=Ministry of Health|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Cases have occurred in all 20 [[district health board]] areas of the country.\n\nThe outbreak has been managed via an [[#Alert level system|alert level system]]. Beginning on 26 March, [[New Zealand Government|the government]] implemented level four \u2013 a [[Curfews and lockdowns related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|nationwide lockdown]]. Individuals are only allowed to leave their living quarters for certain activities such as accessing essential services, and are only allowed to maintain close contact with persons from the same household. Since 10 April, New Zealanders returning from overseas must go into a fortnight's supervised quarantine.\n\n== Background ==\n{{main|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] ([[SARS-CoV-2]]) was the cause of a respiratory illness ([[coronavirus disease 2019]], or COVID-19), in a cluster of people in Wuhan, Hubei, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\nbut the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll worldwide.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{COVID-19 NZ}}\nData about the previous day is revealed during Ministry of Health press conferences which typically occur at 1&nbsp;pm every day.\nAll of the following dates and times are in [[New Zealand Time]]: [[NZDT]] (UTC+13:00) until 5 April and [[NZST]] (UTC+12:00) thereafter.\n\n=== January 2020 ===\nOn 28 January, the [[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]] set up the National Health Coordination Centre (NHCC) in response to the outbreak.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/news-items/novel-coronovirus-update-27th-january-2020|title=Novel coronovirus update|date=27 January 2020|access-date=28 January 2020|website=Ministry of Health, New Zealand|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128053944/https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/news-items/novel-coronovirus-update-27th-january-2020|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> An Infectious and Notifiable Diseases Order was issued to take effect from 30 January,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12304015|title=Coronavirus: Health officials now have the power to quarantine anyone infected|date=28 January 2020|access-date=28 January 2020|website=The New Zealand Herald|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128131058/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12304015|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> which required health practitioners to report any suspected cases under the ''[[Health Act 1956]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legislation.govt.nz/act/public/1956/0065/latest/whole.html#DLM308729 |title=Health Act 1956 No 65 (as at 30 January 2020) \u2013 Schedule 1, Section B |website=New Zealand Legislation|access-date=28 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223220623/http://www.legislation.govt.nz/act/public/1956/0065/latest/whole.html |archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== February 2020 ===\nOn 3 February, the New Zealand Government announced that foreign travellers who left from [[China]] would be denied entry to New Zealand, with only New Zealand citizens and permanent residents and their family being allowed to enter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/408675/nz-to-close-doors-on-foreign-travellers-from-china|title=NZ to close doors on foreign travellers from China|date=2 February 2020|website=RNZ|access-date=9 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202043654/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/408675/nz-to-close-doors-on-foreign-travellers-from-china|archive-date=2 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Universities asked for the Government to exempt Chinese students travelling to study in New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Elder|first1=Vaughan|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/campus/university-of-otago/otago-university-ready-accept-chinese-students|title=Otago University ready to accept Chinese students|date=26 February 2020|website=[[Otago Daily Times]]|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226050749/https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/campus/university-of-otago/otago-university-ready-accept-chinese-students|archive-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Forbes|first1=Stephen|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/119985064/coronavirus-university-of-auckland-says-govt-travel-bans-a-political-decision|title=Coronavirus: University of Auckland says Government travel bans a 'political decision'|date=3 March 2020|website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304011842/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/119985064/coronavirus-university-of-auckland-says-govt-travel-bans-a-political-decision|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Foreigners who left China and spent at least 14 days in another country were permitted to enter New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/new-zealand/students-stranded-in-china-finding-ways-around-nzs-coronavirus-travel-ban|title=Students stranded in China finding ways around NZ's coronavirus travel ban|date=26 February 2020|website=[[TVNZ]]|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304011849/https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/new-zealand/students-stranded-in-china-finding-ways-around-nzs-coronavirus-travel-ban|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The ban was extended for an additional eight days on 24 February.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410233/covid-19-travel-restrictions-for-those-coming-from-china-extended|title=Covid-19: Travel restrictions for those coming from China extended|date=24 February 2020|website=RNZ|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306201734/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410233/covid-19-travel-restrictions-for-those-coming-from-china-extended|archive-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 February, the cruise ship ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' was quarantined by Japanese authorities in [[Yokohama]] after passengers were confirmed to have COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Bruek|first1=Hilary|url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/wuhan-coronavirus-photos-inside-diamond-princess-cruise-with-135-sick-2020-2?r=US&IR=T|title=Photos from inside the Diamond Princess cruise ship, where thousands of passengers have been quarantined for a week because of the coronavirus outbreak|date=12 February 2020|website=Business Insider Australia|access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> Eleven New Zealanders were reported to be on board.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/02/coronavirus-new-zealanders-quarantined-on-cruise-ship-won-t-be-evacuated-home.html|title=Coronavirus: New Zealanders quarantined on cruise ship won't be evacuated home|date=10 February 2020|website=RNZ|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304015244/https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/02/coronavirus-new-zealanders-quarantined-on-cruise-ship-won-t-be-evacuated-home.html|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> By 20 February, four New Zealand passengers had tested positive for the virus and were being treated in Japan. Two of them had been due to travel on an evacuation flight being organised by the Australian government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/409919/coronavirus-two-more-nz-cruise-ship-passengers-test-positive|title=Coronavirus: Two more NZ cruise ship passengers test positive|date=20 February 2020|website=RNZ|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304015242/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/409919/coronavirus-two-more-nz-cruise-ship-passengers-test-positive|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 February, a government-chartered flight operated by [[Air New Zealand]] arrived in Auckland from [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei Province]], China. The city of Wuhan had been under lockdown since 23 January.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Lew|first1=Linda|last2=McCarthy|first2=Simone|last3=Huang|first3=Kristin|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048129/life-time-coronavirus-how-wuhan-made-it-through-week-lockdown|title=Life in the time of coronavirus: how Wuhan made it through a week in lockdown|date=30 January 2020|website=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229173249/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048129/life-time-coronavirus-how-wuhan-made-it-through-week-lockdown|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The flight carried 193 passengers, including 54 New Zealand citizens and 44 permanent residents.<ref name=\"TVNZ mercy flight\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/new-zealand/air-nz-mercy-flight-coronavirus-stricken-wuhan-china-arrives-in-auckland|title=Air NZ mercy flight from coronavirus-stricken Wuhan, China arrives in Auckland|date=5 February 2020|website=TVNZ|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304021050/https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/new-zealand/air-nz-mercy-flight-coronavirus-stricken-wuhan-china-arrives-in-auckland|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Thirty-five Australian passengers were transferred to an Australian flight, while the remaining 157 passengers were quarantined in a military facility at [[Whangaparaoa Peninsula|Whangaparaoa]] for 14 days. The passengers were subsequently released on 19 February.<ref name=\"Newshub quarantine\">{{Cite news|last1=Andelane|first1=Lana|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/02/coronavirus-157-wuhan-evacuees-permitted-to-leave-quarantine-in-whangaparaoa.html|title=Coronavirus: 157 Wuhan evacuees permitted to leave quarantine in Whangaparaoa|date=19 February 2020|website=[[Newshub]]|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304021051/https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/02/coronavirus-157-wuhan-evacuees-permitted-to-leave-quarantine-in-whangaparaoa.html|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 February, the Ministry of Health set up a dedicated Healthline freephone number (0800 358 5453) for COVID-19-related calls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstalkzb.co.nz/on-air/mike-hosking-breakfast/audio/ashley-bloomfield-health-officials-set-up-0800-number-for-those-in-self-isolation/|title=Health officials set up 0800 number for those in self-isolation|last=|first=|date=7 February 2020|website=Newstalk ZB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nNew Zealand confirmed its first case on 28 February, a New Zealand citizen in her 60s who had recently visited [[Iran]], returning via [[Bali]], [[Indonesia]], and arriving in New Zealand on 26 February at Auckland. She had two tests for COVID-19 that were negative, but a third test using a more specific sample was positive. She was admitted to [[Auckland City Hospital]].<ref name=MOH28Feb>{{Cite news |url=https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/single-case-covid-19-confirmed-new-zealand|title=Single case of COVID-19 confirmed in New Zealand|access-date=28 February 2020|website=Ministry of Health, New Zealand|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228055315/https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/single-case-covid-19-confirmed-new-zealand|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last1=Cooke|first1=Henry|last2=Chumko|first2=Andre|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/119899280/ministry-of-health-gives-latest-update-on-novel-coronavirus|title=Coronavirus: First case of virus in New Zealand|website=Stuff|access-date=2020-02-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228171221/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/119899280/ministry-of-health-gives-latest-update-on-novel-coronavirus|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410625/new-zealand-confirms-case-of-covid-19-coronavirus|title=New Zealand confirms case of Covid-19 coronavirus|access-date=28 February 2020|website=Radio New Zealand|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228043835/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410625/new-zealand-confirms-case-of-covid-19-coronavirus|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=MOH-cases-details>{{Cite web |url=https://www.health.govt.nz/our-work/diseases-and-conditions/covid-19-novel-coronavirus/covid-19-current-situation/covid-19-current-cases/covid-19-current-cases-details |title=COVID-19 \u2013 current cases details |access-date=29 March 2020 |website=Ministry of Health, New Zealand |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329085339/https://www.health.govt.nz/our-work/diseases-and-conditions/covid-19-novel-coronavirus/covid-19-current-situation/covid-19-current-cases/covid-19-current-cases-details |archive-date=29 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> New Zealand was the 48th country to have a confirmed case of COVID-19.<ref name=MOH28Feb/> Also on 28 February, the Government extended the travel restrictions to include travellers coming from Iran.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410613/coronavirus-new-travel-restrictions-for-iran-announced|title=Coronavirus: New travel restrictions for Iran announced|date=28 February 2020|website=RNZ|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306153013/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410613/coronavirus-new-travel-restrictions-for-iran-announced|archive-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:COVID-19 Key-Message A3-Posters Wash-Hands.pdf|thumb|A poster from \"Unite against COVID-19\", the New Zealand government's official information campaign.]]\n\n=== March 2020 ===\n[[File:Covid-19-Bubble-spread-02-1.gif|thumb|upright=1.6|Part of a campaign in New Zealand to encourage people to self isolate]]\nOn 4 March, a New Zealand woman in her 30s who had returned from [[northern Italy]] on 25 February was confirmed as the second case of the virus in New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/second-case-covid-19-confirmed-nz|title=Second Case of COVID-19 Confirmed in NZ|date=4 March 2020|website=Ministry of Health, New Zealand|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304003940/https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/second-case-covid-19-confirmed-nz|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She had flown into Auckland via [[Singapore]], and subsequently caught domestic flights to and from [[Palmerston North]] on 2 March.<ref name=\"DomPost4March\">{{Cite news|last1=Hunt|first1=Tom|last2=Wiltshire|first2=Laura|last3=Williams|first3=Katarina|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wellington/119994409/coronavirus-second-confirmed-new-zealand-case|title=Coronavirus: Second confirmed NZ case in Auckland, patient took multiple Air NZ flights|date=4 March 2020|website=Dominion Post|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304173351/https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wellington/119994409/coronavirus-second-confirmed-new-zealand-case|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Her partner also displayed symptoms of the virus, and was confirmed as the fourth case on 6 March.<ref name=\"DomPost4March\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/fourth-case-covid-19-confirmed-new-zealand|title=Fourth case of COVID-19 confirmed in New Zealand|website=Ministry of Health, New Zealand|date=6 March 2020|access-date=6 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306032422/https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/fourth-case-covid-19-confirmed-new-zealand|archive-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March, the third confirmed New Zealand case and the first case of local transmission was reported. An Auckland man in his 40s was infected with COVID-19 by a family member who had returned from Iran on 23 February.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410982/live-coronavirus-updates|title=Live: Coronavirus updates|work=[[Radio New Zealand]]|date=5 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305045830/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410982/live-coronavirus-updates|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Three other members of his family had previously been unwell. Two family members had arrived in New Zealand from Iran on 23 February.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/third-case-covid-19-confirmed-new-zealand |title=Third case of COVID-19 confirmed in New Zealand |publisher=Ministry of Health |date=5 March 2020 |access-date=13 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306032509/https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/third-case-covid-19-confirmed-new-zealand |archive-date=6 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 7 March, a fifth case was announced, a woman in her 40s who was the partner of the third case.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/fifth-case-covid-19-fits-pattern-previous-case |title=Fifth case of COVID-19 Fits Pattern of Previous Case |publisher=Ministry of Health |date=7 March 2020 |access-date=13 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312133156/https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/fifth-case-covid-19-fits-pattern-previous-case |archive-date=12 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/411179/health-boss-announces-fifth-coronavirus-case-in-nz|title=Health boss announces fifth coronavirus case in NZ|website=RNZ|date=5 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308151448/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/411179/health-boss-announces-fifth-coronavirus-case-in-nz|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> One of the family members who had returned from Iran was the father of the third case, and is considered a probable case.<ref name=MOH0309>{{Cite news |url=https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/no-new-cases-covid-19 |title=No new cases of COVID-19 |publisher=Ministry of Health |date=9 March 2020 |access-date=13 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309055132/https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/no-new-cases-covid-19 |archive-date=9 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, the [[Director-General of Health]] [[Ashley Bloomfield]] said that eight people from New Zealand had been passengers on the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships#Grand Princess|11\u201321 February cruise]] of ''[[Grand Princess]]'' from San Francisco to Mexico and back and may have been in contact with a confirmed case of COVID-19. All eight had already returned to New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/precautionary-warning-cdcp-relating-grand-princess |title=Precautionary warning from CDCP relating to the Grand Princess |publisher=Ministry of Health |date=6 March 2020 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> One was a woman in her 70s who had been in the hospital for respiratory illness and was discharged and is considered a probable case.<ref name=MOH0309/>\n\nOn 14 March, a sixth confirmed case was announced, an Auckland man in his 60s who had recently returned from the United States. He went into self isolation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/covid-19-6th-case-overseas-link |title=COVID-19 6th Case \u2013 Overseas Link |publisher=Ministry of Health |date=14 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314003211/https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/covid-19-6th-case-overseas-link |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, two more cases were confirmed, bringing the total number of infected in New Zealand to eight. The seventh case was a man who travelled from Australia to Wellington. The eighth case was of a woman who was a visitor from Denmark arriving in Auckland via Doha and then Christchurch, before driving on towards Queenstown, where she became ill and was hospitalised.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120289851/live-coronavirus-update-from-ministry-of-health|title=Coronavirus: Eighth case confirmed in New Zealand|work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315024717/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120289851/live-coronavirus-update-from-ministry-of-health|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, four more cases were confirmed, bringing the total number of infected in New Zealand to 12.<ref name=\"Stuff 12th case\">{{cite news |last1=Sherwood |first1=Sam |title=Dunedin student 12th positive coronavirus case \u2013 high school to close |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120349877/dunedin-man-11th-positive-coronavirus-case |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317064939/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120349877/dunedin-man-11th-positive-coronavirus-case |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ninth and tenth cases were a [[Wellington]] man and his father, who had travelled back from the [[United States]]. The eleventh case was a man from [[Dunedin]], who had travelled back from Germany.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120336762/live-ministry-of-health-coronavirus-press-conference|title=Live: Eleven people have tested positive for coronavirus in NZ|work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317031231/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120336762/live-ministry-of-health-coronavirus-press-conference|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Henry |first1=Dubby |title=Coronavirus: What we know about NZ's 11 Covid-19 cases |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12316883 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317070029/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12316883 |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The twelfth case was a Dunedin high school student who was the son of the eleventh case.<ref name=\"Stuff 12th case\" /><ref name=\"ODT 12th case\">{{cite news |title=Pupil tests positive, school to close |url=https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/pupil-tests-positive-school-close |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=[[Otago Daily Times]] |date=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317064940/https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/pupil-tests-positive-school-close |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the Ministry of Health confirmed that New Zealand had eight new cases of the coronavirus, bringing the total to 20. Four of these new cases were in Auckland, two in the [[Waikato]] region, one in [[Christchurch]], and one in [[Invercargill]].<ref name=\"Newshub 20 cases\">{{cite news |last1=Ensor |first1=Jamie |title=Coronavirus: Eight new cases in New Zealand |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/03/coronavirus-eight-new-cases-in-new-zealand.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=[[Newshub]] |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318142934/https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/03/coronavirus-eight-new-cases-in-new-zealand.html |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Live Covid-19 updates in New Zealand and around the world |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/covid-19/412008/coronavirus-live-covid-19-updates-in-new-zealand-and-around-the-world |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317220213/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/covid-19/412008/coronavirus-live-covid-19-updates-in-new-zealand-and-around-the-world |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the Ministry of Health confirmed another eight new cases of the Coronavirus, bringing the total to 28. Two of the new cases were in Auckland, two in Taranaki, one in Dunedin, one in Queenstown, one in Northland, and one in Rotorua.<ref name=\"28 cases\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318127|title=Watch live: Eight new cases of coronavirus in NZ \u2013 total now 28|date=2020-03-18|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|access-date=2020-03-19|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319083338/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318127|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus update: Eight further cases of Covid-19 in New Zealand |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/412132/coronavirus-update-eight-further-cases-of-covid-19-in-new-zealand |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319004144/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/412132/coronavirus-update-eight-further-cases-of-covid-19-in-new-zealand |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318291|title = Coronavirus: New Covid-19 cases in Dunedin and Queenstown|work= NZ Herald|date = 19 March 2020|access-date = 19 March 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200319082540/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318291|archive-date = 19 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, the Ministry of Health confirmed 11 new cases of the Coronavirus, bringing the total to 39: five in Auckland, two in Waikato, two in Wellington, one in Canterbury, and one in Hawke's Bay. All new cases were associated with overseas travel.<ref>{{cite news |title=Eleven new cases of Covid-19 in NZ \u2013 Health Ministry |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/412214/eleven-new-cases-of-covid-19-in-nz-health-ministry |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320010814/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/412214/eleven-new-cases-of-covid-19-in-nz-health-ministry |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Devlin |first1=Collete |title=Coronavirus: 11 new cases confirmed \u2013 Ministry of Health |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120438591/coronavirus-ministry-of-health-update-on-number-of-virus-cases |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320010814/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120438591/coronavirus-ministry-of-health-update-on-number-of-virus-cases |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, 13 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total to 52. For two of the cases, no link to overseas travel had been discovered and the Ministry of Health was continuing to investigate.<ref name=MOH20200312>{{cite web |url=https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/covid-19-update-21-march |title=COVID-19 update: 21 March |date=21 March 2020 |publisher=Ministry of Health |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321234948/https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/covid-19-update-21-march |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"52 cases\">{{Cite news |last=Coughlan |first=Thomas |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120464350/ministry-of-health-update-on-new-coronavirus-cases-in-new-zealand |title=Coronavirus: 13 new cases in New Zealand, pushing total up to 52 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=21 March 2020 |language=en-nz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321172549/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120464350/ministry-of-health-update-on-new-coronavirus-cases-in-new-zealand |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, 14 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total to 66. 11 of the new cases had a history of international travel. Two of the other cases had attended the World Hereford Conference in Queenstown, which was held on 9\u201313 March and had New Zealand and international delegates.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Watson |first1=Rebecca |title=Coronavirus: 14 more cases confirmed in NZ, total reaches 66 |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/03/coronavirus-52-more-cases-confirmed-in-nz-total-reaches-66.html |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[Newshub]] |date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322022328/https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/03/coronavirus-52-more-cases-confirmed-in-nz-total-reaches-66.html |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: New 